On April [XXX], 2025 at 10:08 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving an SUV on [XXX] and [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was traveling northeast on [XXX] preparing to make a right turn, and stopped in the right lane at a green light at the intersection with [XXX], yielding to a passenger car stopped within the intersection traveling southeast on [XXX]. A May autonomous shuttle (ego) was stopped at a traffic light in autonomous mode. A vehicle approaching from behind coasted into the ego vehicle. Our system responded with a software Health Drop, which immediately took the ego out of autonomous mode (for safety).
Minor damage was reported to our rear sensor and bumper.

A large semi-trailer truck is making a left turn from a street on the right into the oncoming lane in Detroit, MI.  As the May autonomous shuttle (Ego) is slowing, the Autonomous Vehicle Operator (AVO) intervenes to stop earlier.  The manually controlled Ego remains stationary for five seconds.  The AVO then manually reverses two meters to create more space for the trailer intruding into the Egos lane, making contact with a rear vehicle at 0.6 m/s.  Our team looked at the incident and determined that this event was caused by human error - no autonomy software defects led to this incident.

On May [XXX], 2025 at 9:59 AM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in Los Angeles, California was in a collision involving a box truck and trailer on [XXX] at [XXX].

An unoccupied Zoox vehicle in autonomy was stopped at a red light in the right travel lane on southbound [XXX] at the intersection with [XXX] and [XXX] in San Francisco. At that time, a cyclist on an eBike came to a stop in the bike lane to the right of the Zoox vehicle. The cyclist began to proceed before the light turned green and headed straight. After the light turned green, the Zoox vehicle proceeded straight towards [XXX]. While nearly through the intersection, the cyclist abruptly veered left into the path of the Zoox vehicle and accelerated toward the front of the Zoox vehicle in violation of a red crosswalk signal and in violation of the Zoox vehicle's right-of-way. The Zoox vehicle appropriately braked hard in response to the cyclist's maneuver, but contact was unavoidable. The eBike laterally impacted the Zoox vehicle's right front fender and body side, then the cyclist impacted the right front body of the Zoox vehicle. The Zoox vehicle then came to a full stop. The cyclist then rode over to the sidewalk and remained briefly stopped on the sidewalk before getting back on the eBike and riding away. The Zoox vehicle cleared the intersection, then pulled over on [XXX], and shortly after was towed from the scene for inspection. The Zoox vehicle sustained minor damage to the right front body. The police were not called. No injuries were reported nor apparent with the cyclist.
The content of this report is unchanged from the initial report and provides complete information to date for this incident.

A Zoox vehicle (Vehicle 1) in autonomous mode was in the right lane, traveling east on [XXX] in Las Vegas. On November [XXX], 2024, at 9:10am CST, a Cruise autonomous vehicle ("AV") operating in supervised autonomous mode in Houston, Texas was traveling westbound on [XXX] between [XXX] and [XXX]. A Zoox vehicle in autonomous mode was stopped for a red traffic light on northbound [XXX] while preparing to turn left onto westbound [XXX] in San Francisco. After the light turned green the Zoox vehicle began to move forward and then slowed gradually to yield to a pedestrian with right of way in the crosswalk on [XXX]. Just as the Zoox vehicle slowed to almost a stop (0.2 mph), a skateboarder quickly approached the rear of the Zoox vehicle extending their left arm forward and making contact with the right rear corner of the Zoox vehicle. The Zoox vehicle operator then disengaged from autonomy and brought the vehicle to a stop. The skateboarder initially told the Zoox vehicle operator they were not injured but later mentioned they "smacked" their hand and it was "bruised." When asked, however, they declined medical attention. The Zoox vehicle did not sustain damage. The police were not called. The Zoox vehicle camera footage shows that the skateboarder was looking at their cell phone and did not appear to have been looking ahead at the roadway before the time of contact.The content of this report is unchanged from the initial report and provides complete information to date for this incident.

On October [XXX], 2024 at 3:58 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a passenger car on [XXX] at [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was traveling south in the left lane on [XXX] and came to a stop in a queue of traffic for the red traffic light at the intersection with [XXX]. As the Waymo AV approached the intersection and came to a stop, a passenger car which was following behind the Waymo AV at a low rate of speed approached the Waymo AV from behind and partially crossed into the right-hand travel lane. The passenger car continued proceeding slowly forward until the front of the passenger car made contact with the rear of the Waymo AV. After contact occurred, the passenger car remained in contact with the rear of the Waymo AV, and several bystanders approached the passenger car, attempting to communicate with the driver. Once the traffic light turned green, the Waymo AV proceeded through the intersection and pulled over at the curb on the south side of the intersection to avoid obstructing other traffic. While the Waymo AV proceeded through the intersection, the passenger car continued to roll forward into the intersection, and was stopped by several bystanders. Law enforcement communicated to Waymo that the driver of the passenger car was experiencing a medical emergency and was transported from the scene in an ambulance. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. Both vehicles sustained damage.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

The May vehicle was traveling through an intersection with a van in the oncoming left turn lane. As the May vehicle enters the intersection, the van creeps towards its turn. Cruise is submitting this updated report to indicate in the Post-Crash Information section that it has received a California Highway Patrol Traffic Collision Report in connection with the reported incident.  There are no other changes to Cruise's previous submission (30412-6395-3): A Cruise autonomous vehicle (AV), operating in driverless autonomous mode, was at a complete stop in response to a red light on southbound [XXX] at the intersection with [XXX]. A dark colored Nissan Sentra was also stopped in the adjacent lane to the left of the AV. As the Nissan Sentra and the AV proceeded through the intersection after the light turned green, a pedestrian entered the crosswalk on the opposite side of [XXX] across from the vehicles and proceeded through the intersection against a red light. The pedestrian passed completely through the AVs lane of travel but stopped mid-crosswalk in front of the Nissan Sentra. Shortly thereafter, the Nissan Sentra made contact with the pedestrian, deflecting the pedestrian in front of the AV. The AV braked aggressively but, shortly thereafter, made contact with the pedestrian. The AV then attempted to pull over out of traffic, pulling the individual forward, rather than remaining stationary. The driver of the Nissan Sentra left the scene shortly after the collision. Police and Emergency Medical Services (EMS) were called to the scene and the pedestrian was transported by EMS. On November 2, 2023, Cruise submitted a voluntary recall report to NHTSA relating to the AVs response after the collision, based on updated analysis that Cruise performed since the filing of the previous submissions.

Narrative:
VIN # VG9A2CB2CIV[XXX] 
At approximately 5:54 p.m. on Wednesday, August [XXX], 2023, P84, travelling eastbound on [XXX], approached the three-way stop at [XXX] and [XXX]. P84 arrived at the intersection at the same time as two other vehicles: a grey van heading northbound on [XXX] and a red sedan heading westbound on [XXX]. The safety driver yielded to the northbound vehicle, which proceeded to make a right-hand turn eastbound onto [XXX]. After allowing the intersection to clear, the safety driver onboard P84 confirmed that it was safe for the shuttle to proceed through the intersection. As the shuttle entered the intersection, a second vehicle travelling northbound on [XXX], a white sedan, entered the intersection intending a left-hand turn onto westbound [XXX]. Both vehicles entered the intersection simultaneously, subsequently colliding at a low rate of speed in the middle of the intersection.  
At approximately 5:57 p.m., the Beep Command Center (BCC) was informed by the safety driver that P84 was involved in a minor collision with another vehicle at the intersection of [XXX] and [XXX]. The incident response protocol was initiated, and a supervisor dispatched to the scene. Local law enforcement (San Francisco Police Department) was contacted to report the collision but declined to respond given the minor nature of the collision, directing both parties to exchange information. After the Beep supervisor arrived on scene at approximately 6:49 p.m., the safety driver and supervisor removed the shuttle from the roadway and exchanged insurance information with the driver of the other vehicle. 
Damage to both vehicles was noted to be very minor. The shuttle sustained light scuffs, chips, and small paint transfer. The other vehicle sustained a small dent on the fender. Neither vehicle required towing, and both were safely driven from the scene. 
Beeps safety driver was subsequently subjected to a standard post-collision drug & alcohol screening which has since cleared.  
Contributing Factors 
Based on an analysis of the available evidence, Beep has determined the following factors may have contributed to the higher likelihood of a collision occurring in this instance: 
1.The white sedan failed to yield to P84 in accordance with California state law governing intersection priority.
2.The slight bend in P84s path to accommodate the lane shift through the intersection may have reduced the available stopping distance as the white sedan was not perceived as an obstacle in P84s path until it proceeded further into the intersection.
Incident Findings 
Beep developed the following findings regarding this incident:
1.P84 behaved as expected, detecting and maintaining awareness of the white sedan in the moments preceding the collision, commanding hard braking maneuver, and achieving a 3m/s2 deceleration rate once the white sedan encroached on P84s path.
2.The safety driver observed California state law and had the right of way when releasing P84 into the intersection.
3.The safety driver could have avoided the collision by using the emergency stop. The safety driver indicated that they were aware of the other vehicle through the duration of the incident and were aware of the proper procedure in this scenario but panicked in the moment.
Mitigation:
Implement a priority zone to account for the slight bend in the shuttles path and for future vehicles that may fail to yield.

On September [XXX], 2023 at 6:26 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (Waymo AV) operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a passenger car on [XXX] at [XXX]. 
While the Waymo AV was stopped in park waiting to pick up a passenger near the right side curb of the road on westbound [XXX], a passenger car that was passing the stopped Waymo AV made contact with the rear drivers side of the Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AVs Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. Both vehicles sustained damage.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because a vehicle involved was towed away. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On August [XXX], 2023 at 9:01 PM a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a passenger car on [XXX] at [XXX].
The Waymo AV was traveling southwestbound on [XXX] in the second lane from the left as it was approaching [XXX]. As the Waymo AV was proceeding straight through the intersection, the passenger car in the right adjacent lane made a left turn from a straight-only lane onto southeastbound [XXX]. The rear of the passenger car made contact with the front of the Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was not engaged and a test driver was operating the Waymo AV in manual mode. Both the Waymo AV and the passenger car sustained damage.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

Narrative:

A Zoox vehicle in autonomy was proceeding northbound on [XXX] in stop-and-go traffic through an active construction zone. At the same time, an e-scooter traveling near the right curb was passing other slow traffic behind the Zoox vehicle. Before the e-scooter could also pass the Zoox vehicle on the right, the e-scooter weaved away from the curb, seemingly to avoid a drainage grate, and came within a close following distance behind the Zoox vehicle. As the Zoox vehicle came to a stop again for traffic ahead the e-scooter rider did not stop, and the e-scooter made contact with the right rear tail light of the Zoox vehicle. The e-scooter rider remained upright, did not stop to exchange information, and immediately rode off while the Zoox vehicle was still stopped. There were no injuries and police were not called. The damage to the Zoox vehicle was limited to a cracked tail light lens. This 10-Day update provides complete information for this incident.

On April [XXX], 2023 at 10:46 AM PST a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a passenger car on [XXX] at [XXX].
The Waymo AV was traveling southbound on [XXX] in the leftmost lane as it was approaching the intersection with [XXX].  The signal for traffic proceeding south on [XXX] was green for the Waymo AV as it approached the intersection.  As the Waymo AV approached, an individual riding a motorized scooter traveling north on [XXX] proceeded to turn left onto westbound [XXX], across the paths of the Waymo AV and other oncoming vehicles.  The Waymo AV began to brake, and the Waymo AV test driver transitioned to manual mode and brought the Waymo AV to a stop.  A passenger car traveling directly behind the Waymo AV then made contact with the rear of the Waymo AV.  The individual riding the scooter was not contacted by the Waymo AV or any other vehicle.  At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was not engaged and a test driver was operating the Waymo AV in manual mode.  Both the Waymo AV and the passenger car sustained damage, and the individual on the motorized scooter left the scene.
Transdev Alternative Services is reporting this crash under Request No 1 of Standing General Order 2021 01 because a Vulnerable Road User was involved.  Transdev may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.  This is a duplicate of report ID 30531-5088-1.

While attempting a right turn in autonomous mode from westbound [XXX] onto northbound [XXX], the Waymo AV was yielding to traffic approaching from the left. A passenger car behind the Waymo AV proceeded forward and made contact with the rear of the Waymo AV. Transdev Alternative Services is reporting this crash under Request no. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01.  Transdev may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.  This is a duplicate of 30270-5326-1.

On March [XXX], 2023 at 10:43 AM PST a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in Los Angeles, California was in a collision involving an SUV on [XXX] at [XXX].
The Waymo AV was stopped in the center lane of a three-lane road behind a passenger vehicle for a red light facing southwest on [XXX] at [XXX] in autonomous mode. The light turned green while cross-traffic remained backed up in the intersection.  The Waymo AV nudged forward and slowed to a stop, yielding for the blocking cross traffic. An SUV that had been stopped behind the Waymo AV proceeded forward and made contact with the rear of the Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode, and a test driver was present (in the driver's seating position). The Waymo AV sustained damage.
Transdev Alternative Services is reporting this crash under Request no. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01.  Transdev may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.  This is a duplicate of 30270-5325-1.

On January [XXX], 2023 at 1:38 PM PST a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (Waymo AV) operating in Phoenix, Arizona was in a collision with a minibike whose rider was no longer on it on [XXX] at [XXX].
The Waymo AV was traveling in the leftmost lane on eastbound [XXX], with a group of smaller motorcycles, more commonly known as minibikes, traveling in the right adjacent lane next to and ahead of the Waymo AV. A minibike rider in the group lost control and fell off the minibike a short distance ahead of the Waymo AV in the adjacent lane and the minibike, without a rider, tumbled into the Waymo AV's lane. The Waymo AV applied maximum brake force but made contact with the riderless minibike just before coming to a stop. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AVs Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The Waymo AV sustained damage. The minibike was damaged but it is not possible to determine whether all or some of that damage occurred when the minibike fell to the road before the collision. Because we checked on the minibike riders well-being shortly after the crash, Waymo is aware that the individual sustained minor injuries when they fell from the minibike but the subsequent collision with the riderless minibike did not cause those injuries.
Although we do not believe this event falls under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01, we consulted NHTSA and submitted this report at the agencys request on the day of the consultation. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On June [XXX], 2022 at approximately 4:50 PM PST a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (Waymo AV) operating in San Francisco, California allegedly contributed to a collision between a passenger vehicle and a pickup truck on [XXX] at [XXX], according to a claim by the driver of the passenger vehicle.
The Waymo AV was in autonomous mode and preparing to enter southbound [XXX] as a passenger vehicle on [XXX] approached from behind.  A pickup truck was traveling next to the passenger vehicle in the adjacent left lane.  As the passenger vehicle approached the Waymo AV from behind, the passenger vehicle entered the adjacent left lane that was occupied by the pickup truck and maneuvered around the Waymo AV.  The pickup truck proceeded without stopping, and the passenger vehicle's driver shortly after signaled to the Waymo AV test driver to pull over.  The Waymo AV test driver then transitioned to manual mode and pulled over.  Transdev has no data or knowledge of any contact between any of the three vehicles.  There was no contact or collision between the Waymo AV and any other vehicle.  However, the driver and passenger in the passenger vehicle have subsequently alleged injuries based on alleged contact between the pick-up truck and passenger vehicle, which contact their allegations attribute to the behavior of Waymo's AV in a bodily injury claim under Waymo's insurance policy.  Waymo received notice of this insurance claim on July [XXX].
Transdev Alternative Services is reporting this event under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01.  Transdev may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.  This report is a duplicate of 30270-3655-1.

Subject vehicle was on a testing mission in Mountain View, CA.  The vehicle was traveling North-bound on [XXX] operated by the vehicle's Level 4 Automated Driving System and supervised by a safety driver in the driver's designated seating position, and with a safety operator in the front passenger seating position.  Subject vehicle approached a red light to make a right turn East-bound onto [XXX].  The safety operator suggested that the safety driver disengage the ADS and make the turn in manual mode because the vehicle was hesitant in approaching the intersection. The safety driver disengaged the ADS, and, approximately 250ms later, subject vehicle was lightly struck from behind by a white Mazda3.  Having seen debris on the roadway, the driver and operator believed they had run over a rock and did not realize they were hit by the vehicle. After concluding the mission, the driver and operator found damage to a sensor during an inspection.  A subsequent review of video led to discovery of the crash.  No injuries were reported, and law enforcement was not called to the scene.  
In addition to telematics and video, we also have photographs of the vehicle's damaged sensor.

A Cruise autonomous vehicle ("Cruise AV") operating in driverless autonomous mode, was traveling eastbound on [XXX] toward the intersection with [XXX]. As it approached the intersection, the Cruise AV entered the left hand turn lane, turned the left turn signal on, and initiated a left turn on a green light onto [XXX]. At the same time, a Toyota Prius traveling westbound in the rightmost bus and turn lane of [XXX] approached the intersection in the right turn lane. The Toyota Prius was traveling approximately 40 mph in a 25 mph speed zone. The Cruise AV came to a stop before fully completing its turn onto [XXX] due to the oncoming Toyota Prius, and the Toyota Prius entered the intersection traveling straight from the turn lane instead of turning. Shortly thereafter, the Toyota Prius made contact with the rear passenger side of the Cruise AV. The impact caused damage to the right rear door, panel, and wheel of the Cruise AV. Police and Emergency Medical Services were called to the scene, and a police report was filed. The Cruise AV was towed from the scene. Occupants of both vehicles received medical treatment for allegedly minor injuries. [REDACTED CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION]

On November [XXX], 2021 at 8:02 PM PST a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ('Waymo AV') operating in San Francisco, CA was in a collision involving a passenger vehicle at [XXX], [XXX], and [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was traveling southbound on [XXX], a narrow road with vehicles parked on both sides, and approaching the intersection with [XXX] and [XXX]. A passenger vehicle approaching from the right of the Waymo AV on eastbound [XXX] made a left turn in front of the Waymo AV to head northbound on [XXX]. The Waymo AV slowed to a near stop and nudged to its right in order to share the narrow road with the oncoming vehicle and then came to a stop at the stop sign as the oncoming vehicle completed its turn. At approximately 5 mph, the turning passenger vehicle made contact with Waymo AV's sensor hardware housing on the driver side rear corner fender of the stopped Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode, and a test driver was present (in the driver's seating position). The Waymo AV sustained minor damage to the sensor hardware housing (which was the reason for towing the Waymo AV) and the passenger vehicle left the scene without exchanging information.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because a vehicle involved was towed away. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

Subject vehicle was on a testing mission in Sunnyvale, CA.  The vehicle was traveling South-bound on [XXX], an eight-lane divided road, operated by the vehicles Level 4 Automated Driving System and supervised by a safety driver in the drivers designated seating position, and with a safety operator in the front passenger seating position.  Subject vehicle moved to the right of the lane to turn right onto West-bound [XXX], a two-lane road, and made contact with a curb at approximately 13-miles per hour.  The safety driver was monitoring the behavior of a vehicle passing in the left lane for signs that it might enter subject vehicles path and did not see subject vehicle moving toward the curb in time to intervene and avoid contact.  During the incident, the safety driver disengaged the Automated Driving System, and then pulled the vehicle to the side of [XXX] and inspected the vehicle and curb for damage.  After the inspection, the safety driver drove the vehicle back to base with the Automated Driving System disengaged.  Subject vehicle did not sustain tire or wheel damage, but the contact resulted in misalignment.  No other agents were involved, no injuries were reported, and law enforcement was not called to the scene. Post-Crash Information: In addition to telematics and video, we also have photographs of the tires, curb, and alignment calibration information.
